00:01:03,857 --> 00:01:04,837
So we're talking about games.

24
00:01:04,837 --> 00:01:06,919
We're talking about non-game applications as well.

25
00:01:08,267 --> 00:01:12,631
So looking backwards, let's start with just a little bit about Niantic.

26
00:01:12,631 --> 00:01:17,195
I know some people know us as the company that made Pokemon Go or the company that spun

27
00:01:17,195 --> 00:01:22,919
out of Google, which is cool, that's what we are, but we're our own thing too, and the

28
00:01:22,919 --> 00:01:28,944
thing that we're kind of proud about is not in a chess-beady way, but proud of is why

29
00:01:28,944 --> 00:01:30,005
we're doing what we're doing.

30
00:01:30,005 --> 00:01:34,108
And so I want to give you some insight into why we're building these products.

31
00:01:38,812 --> 00:01:42,056
These things never really work when they're supposed to work.

32
00:01:42,056 --> 00:01:42,977
I can push this button.

33
00:01:42,977 --> 00:01:46,501
So why do we do this stuff?

34
00:01:46,501 --> 00:01:50,706
So the journey actually started quite a ways back for us.

35
00:01:50,706 --> 00:01:53,470
There's kind of a through line that connects.

36
00:01:56,941 --> 00:01:59,143
So, for me, it started when I was a kid, actually.

37
00:01:59,143 --> 00:02:02,645
I grew up in a small town, there wasn't a lot to do there.

38
00:02:02,645 --> 00:02:05,648
But at one point, somebody came and they dropped off

39
00:02:05,648 --> 00:02:10,131
grocery bags full of old National Geographic magazines.

40
00:02:10,131 --> 00:02:12,793
And for me, I fell in love with the maps

41
00:02:12,793 --> 00:02:14,174
that you could pull out.

42
00:02:14,174 --> 00:02:16,676
Like, I can still see the one at the Nile Delta

43
00:02:16,676 --> 00:02:19,177
and all of the kingdoms, just amazing stuff.

44
00:02:19,177 --> 00:02:20,458
So I spent hours with those maps.

45
00:02:20,458 --> 00:02:22,980
A few years later, I saved up my money for mowing lawns

46
00:02:22,980 --> 00:02:23,741
and bought a computer.

47
00:02:24,693 --> 00:02:27,095
And so that's kind of my whole story right there.

48
00:02:27,095 --> 00:02:29,556
Like a bunch of National Geographic maps and a computer

49
00:02:29,556 --> 00:02:31,277
and basic and no money to buy any software.

50
00:02:31,277 --> 00:02:33,939
So then things happen.

51
00:02:33,939 --> 00:02:35,880
But that led me through a series of events

52
00:02:35,880 --> 00:02:38,061
to meet some really cool people,

53
00:02:38,061 --> 00:02:39,322
including a guy named Phil Kesslin.

54
00:02:39,322 --> 00:02:41,723
Phil is the CTO of Niantic.

55
00:02:41,723 --> 00:02:43,904
Back then, Phil was an engineer that I met

56
00:02:43,904 --> 00:02:46,165
out of Silicon Graphics.

57
00:02:46,165 --> 00:02:48,787
And we and some colleagues,

58
00:02:48,787 --> 00:02:51,048
Shikai, Owazama, Avi Barzev, Mark Aubin,

59
00:02:51,788 --> 00:02:54,030
Michael Jones, Brian McClendon.

60
00:02:54,030 --> 00:02:56,612
We founded a company, the company was called Keyhole.

61
00:02:56,612 --> 00:02:59,413
It's a small company, we didn't have a ton of resources,

62
00:02:59,413 --> 00:03:03,076
but we had kind of an audacious vision,

63
00:03:03,076 --> 00:03:06,838
an especially audacious vision for a company that size.

64
00:03:06,838 --> 00:03:11,401
We wanted to take 3D technology, new digital satellite

65
00:03:11,401 --> 00:03:13,642
imaging technology, and broadband,

66
00:03:13,642 --> 00:03:15,183
and make a map of the world.

67
00:03:15,844 --> 00:03:17,485
unlike any map that had been made before.

68
00:03:17,485 --> 00:03:20,548
A map of unprecedented level of detail

69
00:03:20,548 --> 00:03:23,130
built on imagery for the entire planet.

70
00:03:23,130 --> 00:03:24,671
So we got started with that.

71
00:03:24,671 --> 00:03:27,594
We actually were acquired by Google along the way.

72
00:03:27,594 --> 00:03:29,956
And with help from a bunch of other talented people

73
00:03:29,956 --> 00:03:33,198
inside of Google, Brett Taylor, Jim Norris.

74
00:03:34,239 --> 00:03:36,402
Andrew Kirmsey, to name a few,

75
00:03:36,402 --> 00:03:38,324
but actually a very large team.

76
00:03:38,324 --> 00:03:41,207
We were able ultimately to realize that vision,

77
00:03:41,207 --> 00:03:44,751
to build a map, and really to put the whole world

78
00:03:44,751 --> 00:03:46,513
on your desktop initially.

79
00:03:46,513 --> 00:03:50,237
And then later we brought it to the palm of your hand

80
00:03:50,237 --> 00:03:53,600
when we brought it to iOS, brought it to the iPhone,

81
00:03:53,600 --> 00:03:54,521
and brought it to Android.

82
00:03:56,176 --> 00:03:57,837
So after we built the map, at that point,

83
00:03:57,837 --> 00:03:59,937
there were thousands of mashup sites,

84
00:03:59,937 --> 00:04:02,759
people doing all kinds of crazy things with maps.

85
00:04:02,759 --> 00:04:04,019
And so we started thinking about,

86
00:04:04,019 --> 00:04:06,840
well, what can you do with a substrate that we've created,

87
00:04:06,840 --> 00:04:08,401
this geographic substrate of the world?

88
00:04:08,401 --> 00:04:11,042
And we also got interested in the kinds of devices

89
00:04:11,042 --> 00:04:13,143
that people were tinkering with that

90
00:04:13,143 --> 00:04:15,724
look like they might come after the cell phone.

91
00:04:15,724 --> 00:04:16,844
They might be that next.

92
00:04:16,964 --> 00:04:18,385
thing that would come.

93
00:04:18,385 --> 00:04:20,866
There were early versions of wearables,

94
00:04:20,866 --> 00:04:24,608
watch-type devices, people were playing around with HMDs,

95
00:04:24,608 --> 00:04:26,890
different kinds of AR glasses.

96
00:04:26,890 --> 00:04:30,432
And so the thinking was, okay, maps, location,

97
00:04:30,432 --> 00:04:32,893
information, the real world,

98
00:04:32,893 --> 00:04:36,995
these things probably combine in some interesting way.

99
00:04:36,995 --> 00:04:40,017
I got interested in part because I became a parent,

100
00:04:40,017 --> 00:04:40,717
I had kids.

101
00:04:41,465 --> 00:04:43,386
And you know, when you become a parent, it's like,

102
00:04:43,386 --> 00:04:45,067
it's your chance to do everything over again.

103
00:04:45,067 --> 00:04:47,028
It's great, it's like you reset.

104
00:04:47,028 --> 00:04:49,289
And so I was thinking about all the places I wanted to go

105
00:04:49,289 --> 00:04:51,891
and explore with my kids.

106
00:04:51,891 --> 00:04:54,392
So we started Niantic with kind of those themes in mind,

107
00:04:54,392 --> 00:04:57,494
like let's see what happens with maps and location,

108
00:04:57,494 --> 00:05:00,755
wearable technology, to build stuff that brings

109
00:05:00,755 --> 00:05:03,176
those worlds together, the digital world

110
00:05:03,176 --> 00:05:04,237
and the physical world.

111
00:05:05,098 --> 00:05:06,782
So we built some products.

112
00:05:06,782 --> 00:05:09,328
By the time we spun out of Google,

113
00:05:09,328 --> 00:05:10,872
Pokemon Go was in development.

114
00:05:10,872 --> 00:05:13,458
And we had a pretty clear notion at that point in time.

115
00:05:13,950 --> 00:05:14,910
of kind of what our value would be.

116
00:05:14,910 --> 00:05:18,533
The things that we wanted to, I mean with software,

117
00:05:18,533 --> 00:05:20,875
you guys know how it is, like you can build anything.

118
00:05:20,875 --> 00:05:23,136
You know, sometimes the hardest thing is to decide

119
00:05:23,136 --> 00:05:24,237
what you actually want to build.

120
00:05:24,237 --> 00:05:26,619
So we said, well let's put some parameters

121
00:05:26,619 --> 00:05:29,941
around our efforts here to guide us in a particular direction.

122
00:05:29,941 --> 00:05:33,244
And the ones that we came up with based on our experiments

123
00:05:33,244 --> 00:05:35,625
and based on the early games that we pushed out

124
00:05:35,625 --> 00:05:38,087
to users and beta tests and so on, were these.

125
00:05:38,087 --> 00:05:40,068
It started with this idea of exploration.

126
00:05:40,068 --> 00:05:42,770
So sort of the key thing that we settled on was,

127
00:05:42,770 --> 00:05:43,471
you know,

128
00:05:44,319 --> 00:05:48,845
In every neighborhood, there's probably a story that's interesting.

129
00:05:48,845 --> 00:05:52,269
There's a mystery that can be built there, everywhere in the world.

130
00:05:52,269 --> 00:05:55,233
So it was this idea of exploration.

131
00:05:55,233 --> 00:05:59,759
The second thing we settled on was, you know, being computer people and spending a lot of

132
00:05:59,759 --> 00:06:01,281
time at our desks.

133
00:06:02,303 --> 00:06:04,364
you know, we realize that hey,

134
00:06:04,364 --> 00:06:08,647
everybody needs a little nudge sometimes to go outside

135
00:06:08,647 --> 00:06:10,489
and get their 10,000 steps in or get their daily workout in.

136
00:06:10,489 --> 00:06:13,651
Maybe some of you have had a chance to check out our garden

137
00:06:13,651 --> 00:06:15,393
over outside the Metreon.

138
00:06:15,393 --> 00:06:17,594
Good, if you get tired of sitting inside,

139
00:06:17,594 --> 00:06:19,176
we've created a nice space for you out there.

140
00:06:19,816 --> 00:06:27,804
And we heard back from some of the early users of our games from Ingress that people who didn't consider themselves athletes really appreciated that

141
00:06:27,804 --> 00:06:33,309
gamified kind of nudge to to exercise. So we we adopted that as one of the three principles.

142
00:06:33,309 --> 00:06:35,211
And then the third one was social.

143
00:06:35,211 --> 00:06:41,337
So the other thing that you know and this really came from feedback not from originally from our own insight, but from what people

144
00:06:41,437 --> 00:06:43,579
told us when they were using our products,

145
00:06:43,579 --> 00:06:47,821
was that they loved the opportunity to meet new people

146
00:06:47,821 --> 00:06:50,423
and have a thing to do together with their friends or family

147
00:06:50,423 --> 00:06:52,344
or parents with their kids outside,

148
00:06:52,344 --> 00:06:54,366
like an activity that people could do together.

149
00:06:54,366 --> 00:06:56,527
Just lots of love, lots of fan mail,

150
00:06:56,527 --> 00:06:58,529
lots of positive reinforcement around that.

151
00:06:58,529 --> 00:07:00,710
So we adopted that as the third principle.

152
00:07:01,677 --> 00:07:03,298
So this is sort of guiding us.

153
00:07:03,298 --> 00:07:06,540
We track our progress, I mean just to give you a sense

154
00:07:06,540 --> 00:07:08,602
of scale of how this is going.

155
00:07:08,602 --> 00:07:09,923
We measure various things.

156
00:07:09,923 --> 00:07:11,584
In terms of the exploration piece,

157
00:07:11,584 --> 00:07:13,765
we measure the total number of places

158
00:07:13,765 --> 00:07:16,787
that have been observed as special, unique places

159
00:07:16,787 --> 00:07:18,668
in neighborhoods where people live

160
00:07:18,668 --> 00:07:21,410
that people have photographed and named and described

161
00:07:21,410 --> 00:07:24,312
and added into this global game board.

162
00:07:24,312 --> 00:07:27,153
So that now numbers in the many millions.

163
00:07:27,153 --> 00:07:29,575
We've opened up that submission process in Pokemon Go,

164
00:07:29,575 --> 00:07:29,815
so it's.

165
00:07:30,195 --> 00:07:33,823
growing rapidly worldwide.

166
00:07:33,823 --> 00:07:36,608
So this idea of stitching together a global game board,

167
00:07:36,608 --> 00:07:38,752
a place that we can play out of all the interesting nooks

168
00:07:38,752 --> 00:07:41,477
and crannies in the world, is going pretty well.

169
00:07:42,789 --> 00:07:45,991
On the exercise front, this one is just,

170
00:07:45,991 --> 00:07:47,031
you know, it blows us away.

171
00:07:47,031 --> 00:07:48,612
We check this number, it's like bigger

172
00:07:48,612 --> 00:07:49,772
every time we check it.

173
00:07:49,772 --> 00:07:52,614
It's currently three billion total kilometers walked.

174
00:07:52,614 --> 00:07:55,055
And it's interesting.

175
00:07:55,055 --> 00:07:59,657
I know here at GDC, maybe four years ago, five years ago,

176
00:07:59,657 --> 00:08:03,179
there was a speaker talking about some of the early efforts

177
00:08:03,179 --> 00:08:05,180
to do outdoor games.

178
00:08:05,180 --> 00:08:06,921
And the conclusion of the talk was,

179
00:08:06,921 --> 00:08:08,461
hey, people aren't gonna go outside and play.

180
00:08:08,461 --> 00:08:09,222
Give up.

181
00:08:09,222 --> 00:08:11,223
Gamers wanna stay seated in their couch.

182
00:08:11,978 --> 00:08:14,940
And I don't know if it was just timing or the evolution

183
00:08:14,940 --> 00:08:17,241
of the technology or that right combination of gameplay

184
00:08:17,241 --> 00:08:19,823
and design and tech, but that's not true.

185
00:08:19,823 --> 00:08:21,824
Like people like to go outside

186
00:08:21,824 --> 00:08:24,826
and they really enjoy that part of the experience.

187
00:08:26,162 --> 00:08:33,367
In terms of social we measured in 2 ways, we measure it in terms of like the formal connections that people form in the game.

188
00:08:33,367 --> 00:08:44,315
We added the friend feature in Pokemon Go last year so you can identify your friends, you can exchange gifts with those friends, you get bonuses for playing together in raids.

189
00:08:44,315 --> 00:08:49,298
So now there are over 190 million friend connections, so lots of activity there.

190
00:08:49,298 --> 00:08:52,320
And we also measured in terms of the events that we hold.

191
00:08:52,600 --> 00:08:57,925
Has anybody been to a GoFest event or a Pokemon Go community day?

192
00:08:57,925 --> 00:09:00,107
Okay, decent number.

193
00:09:00,107 --> 00:09:05,452
So if you haven't been to one, these events look a little bit like music festival,

