00:12:39,922 --> 00:12:43,283
to evolve our work around real world

251
00:12:43,283 --> 00:12:44,484
and around augmented reality.

252
00:12:45,248 --> 00:12:49,111
A lot of people talk about AR and AR games, by the way,

253
00:12:49,111 --> 00:12:50,572
and we really prefer the term real world

254
00:12:50,572 --> 00:12:55,014
because we think it's that fusion of the digital

255
00:12:55,014 --> 00:12:58,416
and the real world that's the interesting part of it.

256
00:12:58,416 --> 00:13:00,617
And AR, sometimes people think AR and it's that technology

257
00:13:00,617 --> 00:13:02,699
of seeing something through a viewfinder,

258
00:13:02,699 --> 00:13:05,520
which is certainly part of what I think of

259
00:13:05,520 --> 00:13:08,462
as the full breadth of augmented reality,

260
00:13:08,462 --> 00:13:09,243
but that's not all of it.

261
00:13:09,243 --> 00:13:11,404
It's really about how you integrate that

262
00:13:11,404 --> 00:13:12,705
with the physical world.

263
00:13:14,023 --> 00:13:16,644
Okay, so behind these games is a platform.

264
00:13:16,644 --> 00:13:19,665
And this is the set of tech that drives the games.

265
00:13:19,665 --> 00:13:22,167
It's evolved with each of these products.

266
00:13:22,167 --> 00:13:24,307
We actually have several projects under development

267
00:13:24,307 --> 00:13:25,648
that have not yet been announced

268
00:13:25,648 --> 00:13:27,309
that are built on the same technology stack.

269
00:13:27,309 --> 00:13:30,070
At present, we have as many people working

270
00:13:30,070 --> 00:13:32,391
on the platform technology as on Pokemon Go itself.

271
00:13:32,391 --> 00:13:35,732
So there's a robust effort to mature this and productize it.

272
00:13:37,213 --> 00:13:45,355
This tech is the part of the system that does the heavy lifting so that we can all play in a single game instance.

273
00:13:45,355 --> 00:13:48,476
So if any of you played World of Warcraft like I did back in the day,

274
00:13:48,476 --> 00:13:54,138
of course we had to pick what server to join when we wanted to join a massively multiplayer game.

275
00:13:54,138 --> 00:13:58,639
The innovation here is that this system holds state for all users in a single...

276
00:13:59,680 --> 00:14:01,902
instance, if you will, of the game.

277
00:14:01,902 --> 00:14:05,626
It's, of course, striped across tens of thousands of servers,

278
00:14:05,626 --> 00:14:07,228
but you don't have to think about that as a player.

279
00:14:07,228 --> 00:14:11,252
This system also supports all the social features that I've talked about,

280
00:14:11,252 --> 00:14:13,955
all the mapping, all the location,

281
00:14:13,955 --> 00:14:15,577
information that's integrated into that,

282
00:14:15,577 --> 00:14:20,262
really all the support that you need to develop and publish a game like this.

283
00:14:20,922 --> 00:14:22,203
And of course, advanced AR.

284
00:14:22,203 --> 00:14:25,085
And we're gonna spend maybe the rest of the talk

285
00:14:25,085 --> 00:14:26,266
talking about the advanced AR part.

286
00:14:26,266 --> 00:14:30,288
That gives you a common layer between

287
00:14:30,288 --> 00:14:31,169
ARKit and ARCore,

288
00:14:31,169 --> 00:14:34,851
and also provides a way for us to extend that functionality

289
00:14:34,851 --> 00:14:37,612
with cloud-based AR capability.

290
00:14:37,612 --> 00:14:40,734
And that's where a lot of our R&D is going.

291
00:14:41,735 --> 00:14:44,859
We do have a developer contest that's open right now,

292
00:14:44,859 --> 00:14:47,382
the Niantic Beyond Reality Contest.

293
00:14:47,382 --> 00:14:51,406
There are a million dollars in prizes for that contest.

294
00:14:51,406 --> 00:14:53,148
It's open for submissions until the end of the month.

295
00:14:53,148 --> 00:14:56,953
There'll be a sort of game jam session through the summer

296
00:14:56,953 --> 00:14:59,436
where we'll be working with the finalists.

297
00:14:59,436 --> 00:15:01,038
And we've set aside.

298
00:15:01,551 --> 00:15:04,272
actually several tens of millions of dollars to fund,

299
00:15:04,272 --> 00:15:07,314
hopefully some projects that emerge out of that,

300
00:15:07,314 --> 00:15:09,334
beyond the prize money, and also other projects

301
00:15:09,334 --> 00:15:11,235
that we'll identify next year.

302
00:15:11,235 --> 00:15:13,656
So something to check out if you're interested

303
00:15:13,656 --> 00:15:16,598
in building products like this.

304
00:15:16,598 --> 00:15:18,378
Why do we want to see more games like this?

305
00:15:18,378 --> 00:15:22,240
One of the reasons that we do our events like this,

306
00:15:22,240 --> 00:15:25,142
so I talked about our Niantic-hosted events.

307
00:15:25,142 --> 00:15:27,242
Within that are a subset of things

308
00:15:27,242 --> 00:15:29,003
that we do with civic organizations.

309
00:15:30,263 --> 00:15:31,243
So we think about technology.

310
00:15:31,243 --> 00:15:34,226
There's a lot of bad press about tech right now.

311
00:15:34,226 --> 00:15:35,566
I think that tech can actually have

312
00:15:35,566 --> 00:15:37,007
a very positive impact on the world,

313
00:15:37,007 --> 00:15:38,909
and this is one example of that.

314
00:15:38,909 --> 00:15:40,410
We partnered with the Knight Foundation.

315
00:15:40,410 --> 00:15:43,292
They do a lot of work in cities that are distressed,

316
00:15:43,292 --> 00:15:44,633
that are trying to rebuild,

317
00:15:44,633 --> 00:15:46,574
that have serious economic and social problems.

318
00:15:46,934 --> 00:15:48,956
And one of the ways they do that is they host festivals

319
00:15:48,956 --> 00:15:52,399
to get people into the city and just walking the streets,

320
00:15:52,399 --> 00:15:56,063
meeting their neighbors, rediscovering what's there.

321
00:15:56,063 --> 00:15:59,426
So, Soclavia in Los Angeles is an example of that.

322
00:15:59,426 --> 00:16:02,789
The Philly Free Streets Initiative is another.

323
00:16:02,789 --> 00:16:05,051
There's a UK org that we work with

324
00:16:05,051 --> 00:16:06,913
which is independent of the Knight Foundation.

325
00:16:07,613 --> 00:16:11,477
called Big Heritage and they're devoted to teaching history to kids

326
00:16:11,477 --> 00:16:14,979
by having these big festival style events, families come together

327
00:16:14,979 --> 00:16:18,422
and then they learn about the history of the town

328
00:16:18,422 --> 00:16:22,986
in this really fun interactive way. So in all these cases we're overlaying gameplay.

329
00:16:23,506 --> 00:16:26,126
onto an existing kind of civic festival,

330
00:16:26,126 --> 00:16:27,907
dramatically increasing their attendance

331
00:16:27,907 --> 00:16:29,207
and drawing in an audience that wouldn't

332
00:16:29,207 --> 00:16:31,087
otherwise probably attend.

333
00:16:31,087 --> 00:16:33,348
So we want to see more events like this,

334
00:16:33,348 --> 00:16:35,688
and that means opening up our platform

335
00:16:35,688 --> 00:16:37,949
so that many people can build,

336
00:16:37,949 --> 00:16:39,969
hopefully really fun experiences on top of it.

337
00:16:39,969 --> 00:16:43,209
Okay, so what have we learned?

338
00:16:43,209 --> 00:16:45,370
You know, this is the part where we share

339
00:16:45,370 --> 00:16:48,470
some of our stubbed toes,

340
00:16:48,470 --> 00:16:50,611
some of the mistakes that we've made.

341
00:16:52,029 --> 00:16:56,397
You know, the first one is really a message of encouragement

342
00:16:56,397 --> 00:17:01,988
about the potential to build games that are broadly inclusive

343
00:17:01,988 --> 00:17:03,130
and broadly appealing.

344
00:17:03,747 --> 00:17:08,813
Whenever I first started investigating the idea of us doing a game,

345
00:17:08,813 --> 00:17:12,538
I was doing my research and people talked about casual games and mid-core games.

346
00:17:12,538 --> 00:17:17,804
And casual games had a certain look and feel, they attracted a certain audience,

347
00:17:17,804 --> 00:17:19,646
they had strengths and weaknesses.

348
00:17:19,646 --> 00:17:23,131
Mid-core games were for real gamers and they had a completely separate dynamic to them.

349
00:17:23,611 --> 00:17:27,575
And then there are hardcore games or like the real serious console games.

350
00:17:27,575 --> 00:17:31,619
We didn't want to put ourselves into a single category.

351
00:17:31,619 --> 00:17:38,305
We wanted to build something that was broadly appealing, but we had ambitions around retention.

352
00:17:38,305 --> 00:17:40,728
We wanted it to be financially successful.

353
00:17:41,628 --> 00:17:44,269
And so this was a risky shot for us.

354
00:17:44,269 --> 00:17:48,470
And what I'm reporting back to you is that it is possible

355
00:17:48,470 --> 00:17:51,912
to build this kind of game, and I don't think it fits

356
00:17:51,912 --> 00:17:54,512
an existing category, I wanna call them accessible games.

357
00:17:54,512 --> 00:17:57,173
You know, games that are gonna appeal to males, females,

358
00:17:57,173 --> 00:17:58,674
people from all walks of life,

359
00:17:58,674 --> 00:18:00,314
multiple demographics and age groups.

360
00:18:01,815 --> 00:18:04,256
With Go today, based on third party research,

361
00:18:04,256 --> 00:18:06,518
polls that have been done,

362
00:18:06,518 --> 00:18:09,579
we see more than 40% of the players are women.

363
00:18:09,579 --> 00:18:12,801
We see underrepresented minorities in excess of 30%,

364
00:18:12,801 --> 00:18:15,182
which is great.

365
00:18:15,182 --> 00:18:18,664
That begins to approach what the world looks like

366
00:18:18,664 --> 00:18:19,905
in terms of those distributions.

367
00:18:19,905 --> 00:18:21,686
So gamers, not a subset of the world,

368
00:18:21,686 --> 00:18:25,028
gamers are just, they look like everybody else.

369
00:18:26,373 --> 00:18:31,397
And we've seen very good long-term retention,

370
00:18:31,397 --> 00:18:32,757
good spend in terms of the revenue.

371
00:18:32,757 --> 00:18:34,979
So it's possible to build broad games that

372
00:18:34,979 --> 00:18:38,281
keep people for a long period of time playing very intensively.

373
00:18:38,281 --> 00:18:42,203
So mid-core, casual, there's something in between, I think.

374
00:18:44,589 --> 00:18:47,652
So AR, I want to tackle this head on,

375
00:18:47,652 --> 00:18:50,634
because I know you guys, many people are probably curious

376
00:18:50,634 --> 00:18:52,335
about AR, many people are thinking about starting

377
00:18:52,335 --> 00:18:58,640
AR projects, and we've had some learnings here, right?

378
00:18:58,640 --> 00:19:03,884
AR in and of itself is not a magic bullet for a hit game.

379
00:19:03,884 --> 00:19:05,825
There are some real drawbacks to it.

380
00:19:05,825 --> 00:19:10,989
The ergonomics are one of them.

381
00:19:10,989 --> 00:19:11,750
We know that...

382
00:19:14,422 --> 00:19:15,382
Oops.

383
00:19:15,382 --> 00:19:18,765
We know that people really don't like to hold up their

384
00:19:18,765 --> 00:19:20,386
phones for long periods of time.

385
00:19:20,386 --> 00:19:24,950
We think the right session length for holding up your phone

386
00:19:24,950 --> 00:19:27,832
is not more than two to three minutes, for example.

387
00:19:27,832 --> 00:19:30,214
So if you think about AR, you wanna think about it

388
00:19:30,214 --> 00:19:33,016
as a type of play that happens within a broader game

389
00:19:33,016 --> 00:19:37,280
where a lot of the gameplay is not happening in AR mode.

390
00:19:38,680 --> 00:19:39,861
Social stigma.

391
00:19:39,861 --> 00:19:41,921
So when you hold up your phone and you wave it around,

392
00:19:41,921 --> 00:19:44,022
it looks like you might be taking a picture

393
00:19:44,022 --> 00:19:46,362
of everybody who's standing around you.

394
00:19:46,362 --> 00:19:49,403
This is a big drawback to AR in certain situations

395
00:19:49,403 --> 00:19:51,603
and is something that really needs to be designed around.

396
00:19:51,603 --> 00:19:54,324
The other thing is just efficiency.

397
00:19:54,324 --> 00:19:55,564
And by that, I mean two things.

398
00:19:55,564 --> 00:19:58,305
Device efficiency, so there's a power drain

399
00:19:58,305 --> 00:19:59,425
that one has to take into account.

400
00:19:59,425 --> 00:20:03,026
And there's also just gameplay, game loop efficiency.

401
00:20:03,026 --> 00:20:04,807
If people are power leveling through a game.

402
00:20:05,222 --> 00:20:08,422
they're not maybe happy to take that extra time it takes

403
00:20:08,422 --> 00:20:12,623
to instantiate an AR session and play in that way.

404
00:20:12,623 --> 00:20:15,784
So, short sessions and really thoughtful design.

405
00:20:15,784 --> 00:20:18,765
We think the right approach here is to design things

406
00:20:18,765 --> 00:20:22,185
for AR that really can't be done outside of AR.

407
00:20:22,185 --> 00:20:26,186
So to try to think of game mechanics where you're

408
00:20:26,186 --> 00:20:27,827
in AR mode and it's obvious why you're there,

409
00:20:27,827 --> 00:20:29,447
you're having an experience that you can really

410
00:20:29,447 --> 00:20:32,028
only realize through AR.

411
00:20:33,352 --> 00:20:39,238
The other thing that I want to sort of flag here is you hear a lot of hype in the industry

412
00:20:39,238 --> 00:20:44,384
about augmented reality. You hear it from large tech companies other than us, like the really,

413
00:20:44,384 --> 00:20:49,370
really big tech companies. You hear us talking about AR. It's important to understand that

414
00:20:49,370 --> 00:20:53,275
sometimes when we talk about it, and certainly when some of the other companies talk about it,

415
00:20:54,468 --> 00:20:56,630
Really talking about the potential for AR in devices

416
00:20:56,630 --> 00:20:59,072
that are going to come after the phone.

417
00:20:59,072 --> 00:21:03,876
So there are inherent limitations to AR in phones.

418
00:21:03,876 --> 00:21:05,798
I, for one, don't believe that AR

419
00:21:05,798 --> 00:21:07,679
is going to take over the phone and everybody's just

420
00:21:07,679 --> 00:21:09,180
going to walk around in AR mode all the time.

421
00:21:09,180 --> 00:21:12,023
That's definitely not going to happen.

422
00:21:13,064 --> 00:21:14,725
But I do believe there's huge potential.

423
00:21:14,725 --> 00:21:16,226
I believe that potential is going

424
00:21:16,226 --> 00:21:17,947
to come in future devices.

425
00:21:17,947 --> 00:21:21,269
Having said that, there's huge incentive for all of us

426
00:21:21,269 --> 00:21:24,231
to try to learn about AR, to learn what works and doesn't

427
00:21:24,231 --> 00:21:28,054
work, to evolve the technology on mobile devices today.

428
00:21:28,054 --> 00:21:31,656
So a lot of the interest you see from other tech companies

429
00:21:31,656 --> 00:21:34,478
that I won't name by name and us is

430
00:21:34,478 --> 00:21:37,360
trying to figure out this technology

431
00:21:37,360 --> 00:21:40,182
and advance it and evolve it while this other kind

432
00:21:40,182 --> 00:21:41,843
of hardware is being developed.

433
00:21:43,994 --> 00:21:46,697
So, what's the killer feature for a real world AR game?

434
00:21:46,697 --> 00:21:49,019
You know, some people ask that of us a lot,

435
00:21:49,019 --> 00:21:50,660
and I don't think it's the AR.

436
00:21:50,660 --> 00:21:54,224
I think AR is nice embellishment on top.

437
00:21:54,224 --> 00:21:55,685
It's the icing on the cake.

438
00:21:55,685 --> 00:22:00,089
The things that we think are really the killer features

439
00:22:00,089 --> 00:22:02,011
for games of this type are the ones that we adopted

440
00:22:02,011 --> 00:22:02,811
as our core principles.

441
00:22:02,811 --> 00:22:04,753
That's why we adopted them.

442
00:22:04,753 --> 00:22:06,915
But it is exploration, exercise,

443
00:22:06,915 --> 00:22:08,256
and real world social interactions.

444
00:22:09,480 --> 00:22:13,800
In terms of the, you know, I said earlier we had 3 million people come to events that we host.

445
00:22:14,959 --> 00:22:17,821
Pokemon Go players organize their own event once a month,

446
00:22:17,821 --> 00:22:19,102
it's called Community Day.

447
00:22:19,102 --> 00:22:21,163
We support it with a little live ops programming

448
00:22:21,163 --> 00:22:22,324
behind the scenes.

449
00:22:22,324 --> 00:22:24,025
But there were over 100 million players

450
00:22:24,025 --> 00:22:26,967
that participated in Community Day last year.

451
00:22:26,967 --> 00:22:30,950
So intense interest in people getting together in real life.

452
00:22:30,950 --> 00:22:35,453
And we think there are reasons behind the exercise

453
00:22:35,453 --> 00:22:38,115
and the real world social that are pretty obvious.

454
00:22:38,115 --> 00:22:41,117
Both of those things make people feel better, ultimately.

455
00:22:41,117 --> 00:22:43,979
So there's a feedback loop there that's driving that.

456
00:22:46,370 --> 00:22:49,571
Okay, so that's the past, all right?

457
00:22:49,571 --> 00:22:51,231
Now it's time to look towards the future.

458
00:22:51,231 --> 00:22:55,133
So what is the interesting technology that we're working on

459
00:22:55,133 --> 00:22:57,834
and other people are working on with AR?

460
00:22:57,834 --> 00:22:59,994
We're gonna get into the meat of that.

461
00:22:59,994 --> 00:23:03,536
So the way I like to characterize it

462
00:23:03,536 --> 00:23:05,817
is connecting the atoms and the bits.

463
00:23:05,817 --> 00:23:10,318
So if AR sort of V1 is open your phone,

464
00:23:10,318 --> 00:23:11,138
see a hologram,

465
00:23:12,382 --> 00:23:15,204
Maybe it is sort of situated more or less accurately

466
00:23:15,204 --> 00:23:17,166
in space, it's glued to the ground.

467
00:23:17,166 --> 00:23:19,588
It doesn't really know where it is.

468
00:23:19,588 --> 00:23:21,429
It's not really part of the world.

469
00:23:21,429 --> 00:23:22,970
It's sort of a parlor trick.

470
00:23:22,970 --> 00:23:26,133
It's an illusion that's fun,

471
00:23:26,133 --> 00:23:28,175
but there are limits to how far you can take that.

472
00:23:28,175 --> 00:23:32,578
So ARv2 is about really connecting those bits,

473
00:23:32,578 --> 00:23:34,500
the thing that we make in the computer

474
00:23:34,500 --> 00:23:35,921
with the atoms of the world.

475
00:23:35,921 --> 00:23:40,385
And having those objects be grounded in specific locations

476
00:23:40,885 --> 00:23:42,947
being aware of those locations,

477
00:23:42,947 --> 00:23:44,209
being shareable, and being persistent.

478
00:23:44,209 --> 00:23:47,091
So when we think about what's next,

479
00:23:47,091 --> 00:23:52,316
there are three kind of key areas of technology development

480
00:23:52,316 --> 00:23:55,039
that we think are essential to realize that vision

481
00:23:55,039 --> 00:23:56,080
that I just described.

482
00:23:56,080 --> 00:23:58,182
The first is mapping,

483
00:23:58,182 --> 00:24:00,684
and I'm gonna talk about each of these in more detail.

484
00:24:00,684 --> 00:24:03,347
The second is understanding or interpreting

485
00:24:03,347 --> 00:24:05,889
that flow of pixels that's coming into the device.

486
00:24:06,533 --> 00:24:09,534
And the third is sharing, the ability for all of us

487
00:24:09,534 --> 00:24:12,115
to have a common, shared experience with AR.

488
00:24:12,115 --> 00:24:15,456
None of these are really possible with today's technology.

489
00:24:15,456 --> 00:24:18,717
So each of these three areas are new things

490
00:24:18,717 --> 00:24:21,618
that need to be invented.

491
00:24:21,618 --> 00:24:23,538
So let me talk about mapping first.

492
00:24:23,538 --> 00:24:24,659
I think this is,

493
00:24:24,659 --> 00:24:28,119
this is the one that's near and dear to my heart.

494
00:24:28,119 --> 00:24:30,740
It is a continuation in some ways of the work that we did.

495
00:24:31,484 --> 00:24:33,346
on Google Earth and Google Maps.

496
00:24:33,346 --> 00:24:35,088
But it's really different in some ways as well,

497
00:24:35,088 --> 00:24:40,253
because we made Google Earth and Google Maps for all of you.

498
00:24:40,253 --> 00:24:41,695
We made it for people.

499
00:24:41,695 --> 00:24:44,698
It's designed to be a fun, friendly, accessible UI

500
00:24:44,698 --> 00:24:48,141
for human beings so that we can never be lost again.

501
00:24:48,141 --> 00:24:50,183
We can navigate wherever we want in the world.

502
00:24:50,183 --> 00:24:54,027
The AR maps that we're building are built for machines.

503
00:24:54,408 --> 00:24:57,289
